e social and economic past that contradicts traditional “prairie” narratives around settlement, economic development, and culture. She offers a refreshing new perspective that overturns long-held assumptions of the prairies and the Canadian west.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEcotones-Saskatchewan. 0aHuman ecology--Saskatchewan--History. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh  aagriculture.  aecology.  aenvironment.  aforestry.  aland use.  aresource extraction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755452040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887554520423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887554520/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles